QUALIFICATION: authorship of insularis is often ascribed to White, to whom Walker attributed the name: 'Termes insularis, White, Zool. Erebus and Terror, fig. 11.' In 1853 White's figure was unpublished; it finally appeared in 1874, as the second part of White, A. & Butler, A.G. 1846. Insects. pp. 1-51 pls1-10 in Richardson, J. & Gray, J.E. (eds). The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Erebus & Terror, under the command of Sir James Clark Ross, R.N., F.R.S., during the years 1839 to 1843. London : E.W. Janson . (see Rye, E.C. 1876. Insecta. The general subject. pp. 239-247 in Rye, E.C. Zoological Record for 1874. London : J. van Voorst . [239]), without descriptive text but with bibliographic entries that Butler had brought up-to-date, including reference to 'White Ms., tab. 7, f. 11.' Walker did not include White's illustration, and the detailed description that forms the indication for the specific name must be attributed to Walker

QUALIFICATION: Hill, G.F. 1942. Termites (Isoptera) from the Australian Region. Melbourne : Council for Scientific and Industrial Research 479 pp. 24 pls. [341] commented that 'No information is available regarding the whereabouts of the holotype soldier and morphotype worker' of H. obeuntis. Silvestri, F. 1909. Isoptera. pp. 279-314 pls xvi-xxi in Michaelsen, W. & Hartmeyer, R. (eds). Die Fauna Südwest-Australiens. Vol. 2. Jena : Fischer . did not mention types and, as Hill did not identify a particular specimen, his comment cannot be regarded as a lectotype designation. Weidner, H. 1955. Die Typen der Isoptera-Sammlung des Zoologischen Staatsinstituts und Zoologischen Museums Hamburg. Insectes Sociaux 2: 247-254 [249] listed 'Königin, Sold., Arb.' of H. obeuntis among the type specimens of termites in the collections of the Zoologisches Institut und Zoologisches Museum der Universit?t, Hamburg; these were, therefore, syntypes. The relevant vial in ZMH contains a queen, not of a species of Amitermes, a soldier of what has long been regarded as A. obeuntis, plus a nymph and 12 workers, not all of A. obeuntis. There is also a label in A.E. Emerson's hand 'LECTOTYPE SOLDIER' (as symbol for \ma) 'Serpentine S.W. Australia. No. 131. Selected A. Emerson. 57'. The lectotype designation was not published

Suppl. 4: 1-172 summarised the nomenclatorial history of Nasutitermes Dudley, which was described without included species; unfortunately, Sands missed two important points: first, that Banks, N. 1918. The termites of Panama and British Guiana. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 38: 659-667 pl. LI used the name Nasutitermes for Termes cornigera Motschulsky, 1855, making cornigera an originally included nominal species of Nasutitermes Dudley and second, that Banks in Banks, N. & Snyder, T.E. 1920. A revision of the Nearctic termites with notes on biology and geographic distribution. Bull. U.S. Natl. Mus. 108: viii 1-228 described Nasutitermes as a new genus with Termes morio Latreille, 1805 as type species; Nasutitermes Banks, 1920, is thus a junior homonym of Nasutitermes Dudley, 1890 (as well as being a subjective junior synonym), so that the identity of Termes morio is irrelevant to the question of the type species of Nasutitermes Dudley; Emerson, A.E. 1925. The termites of Kartabo Bartica District, British Guiana. Zoologica N.Y. 6: 291-459 chose Eutermes costalis Holmgren, 1910 as type species of Nasutitermes Banks, again a choice irrelevant to Nasutitermes Dudley; Snyder, T.E. 1949. Catalog of the termites (Isoptera) of the world. Smithson. Misc.
